SIMPLE: harden
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harden
<hw>Hard"en</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧rd"'n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hardened</conjf>
<pr>(-'nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Hardening</conjf>
<pr>(-'n*⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hardnen</ets>,
<ets>hardenen</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make hard or harder; to
make firm or compact; to indurate; <as>as, to <ex>harden</ex> clay or
iron</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To accustom by labor or suffering to endure with
constancy; to strengthen; to stiffen; to inure; also, to confirm in
wickedness or shame; to make unimpressionable.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Harden</xex> not your heart.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ps. xcv.
8.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would <qex>harden</qex> myself in sorrow.</q> <rj><qau>Job vi.
10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harden</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harden
<hw>Hard"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become hard or
harder; to acquire solidity, or more compactness; <as>as, mortar
<ex>hardens</ex> by drying</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The deliberate judgment of those who knew him [A. Lincoln] has
<qex>hardened</qex> into tradition.</q> <rj><qau>The
Century.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become confirmed or strengthened, in either a
good or a bad sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They, <qex>hardened</qex> more by what might most reclaim.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hardenbergia</ent>⟦br⟧
